00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:06.479
So, Shakespeare based Hamlet on a medieval
Scandinavian tale chronicled by everyone’s

00:01:06.479 --> 00:01:11.100
favorite Danish historian Saxo Grammaticus,
pictured here, depending on your world view

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:14.350
as either Santa Claus or God.
But shakespeare probably knew the tale from

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:18.850
contemporary plays rather than like actual
Danish history because up to that point had

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:22.910
been mostly about Vikings and pastries. Actually,
that’s still mostly what it is.

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:27.400
So Saxo tells the story of Prince Amleth,
a kid who he sees his uncle murder his father.

00:01:27.409 --> 00:01:32.479
And then young Amleth bides his time and pretends
to be crazy in order to lull his uncle into

00:01:32.479 --> 00:01:36.819
a false sense of security. And then, as soon
as he’s grown up, Amleth slaughters his

00:01:36.819 --> 00:01:41.499
uncle with his father’s sword.
Amleth by the way, 80% of the way to being

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:44.200
Pig Latin for Hamlet.
Anyway, it’s interesting to know that background

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:47.719
because it makes you think about the changes
that Shakespeare makes to that story which

00:01:47.719 --> 00:01:51.119
indicates something about what’s really
important to Shakespeare.

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:54.780
For instance, Hamlet isn’t unable to kill
his uncle because he’s young. And he doesn’t

00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:59.300
actually see his uncle murder his father.
So basically, Shakespeare was introducing

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:02.360
ambiguity into the story which is kind of
Shakespeare’s specialty.

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:06.060
So Hamlet is Shakespeare’s most popular
play, in fact, it’s perhaps the only one

00:02:06.069 --> 00:02:10.920
to have been consistently performed since
it debuted. It’s also, very long.

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:15.720
Like when Kenneth Branagh attempted to film
every line the movie lasted more than four

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:19.470
hours. Some theatrical productions have gone
on as long as six.

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:24.110
The general consensus is that Shakespeare
wrote the play so long to satisfy himself,

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:28.070
and he knew that theatre troupes would just
like make it shorter any way they wanted.

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:31.920
But it’s also possible that he thought that
by keeping the audience at the theater for

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:34.870
longer, would help him to sell more
mutton pies at the concession stand.

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:39.120
We have to remember art is also commerce.
But this whole link thing brings us to the

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:43.090
fact that there are actually three different
versions of Hamlet. There are two quartos,

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:48.560
one from 1603 and another from 1604, and then
the Folio edition from 1623

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:52.830
The second quarto and the folio are somewhat
similar, although the first was probably based

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:56.460
on Shakespeare’s notes and the second based
on seeing the play in performance.

00:02:56.460 --> 00:03:00.650
But the first quarto is known as the “bad
quarto,” and not in the sense that it’s

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:02.950
evil, but in the sense that it’s kind of
terrible.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:07.300
Historians believe that an actor probably
transcribed the first quarto his memory and

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:11.860
that that actor probably only played really
small parts. Like Marcellus.

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:16.620
Basically, the scenes he was onstage for he remembered pretty well, but the other ones not so much.

00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:20.940
He was probably that actor who's always
mouthing other peoples' lines. For example,

00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:27.720
here’s the bad quarto’s  “To be or not to be” speech:
“To be, or not to be, that's the point,

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:34.280
to die, to sleepe, is that all?” Yeah, that's fantastic.
Anyway, in all the versions, the plot is the same:

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:38.020
Hamlet is a grad student who returns
home to Elsinore when his father dies and

00:03:38.030 --> 00:03:43.170
then his mother Gertrude suddenly marries
his uncle Claudius. Claudius takes over as

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:45.760
king even though technically Hamlet should
inherit the throne.

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:49.850
So a grieving Hamlet deals with this as any
grad student would by wearing black, listening

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:54.380
to sad music, and making long speeches about
how he wishes his flesh would melt. Which

00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:58.430
spoiler: It eventually will.
But then, his father’s ghost appears to

00:03:58.430 --> 00:04:04.600
him and begs Hamlet to revenge his murder
by that aforementioned uncle Claudius. Hamlet

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:08.330
isn’t sure about this. So he pretends to
be insane, you know as you do.

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:11.550
He then hires a troupe of players
to put on a show that will make Claudius to

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:14.319
reveal his guilt,
Claudius is indeed overwhelmed with emotion,

00:04:14.319 --> 00:04:18.840
flees the play, Gertrude summons Hamlet to
her bedchamber where they have a weirdly intimate

00:04:18.840 --> 00:04:24.280
discussion, until Hamlet hears a noise and
in a rare decisive moment stabs the curtain.

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:27.770
Oh, but it’s not my uncle, it’s Polonius.

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:31.720
Polonius, who was never brief despite saying
that, “brevity is the soul of wit.”

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:35.510
And then also famously said, “to thine own
self be true” and you know, proceeded to

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:38.220
not be terribly true to himself.
So Gertrude decides that Hamlet should get

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:42.300
out of town for a while and he sails away
and there’s a writ of death and storms and

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:47.720
pirates, and then Hamlet returns only to find
that Polonius’s daughter Ophelia has committed

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:52.160
suicide and that her brother Laertes is kind
of mad at Hamlet.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:56.639
So Claudius schedules a fencing match between
Laertes and Hamlet, poisoning Laertes’s

00:04:56.639 --> 00:05:01.660
sword and Hamlet’s wine.
Hamlet is stabbed, but manages to wound Laertes

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:07.430
while Gertrude downs the fatal wine. And then,
once everyone is dead or dying Hamlet decides

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:12.430
that, now, is finally a good time to stab
Claudius.

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:17.300
Basically, all the Danes die. Except Horatio
of course because you need someone to say,

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:20.960
“Good night sweet prince: And flights of
angels sing thee to thy rest!”

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:25.340
What kind of place is this Denmark where people
have stunningly un-Danish names like Claudius

00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:27.710
and Polonius. Well, let’s go to the Thought
Bubble.

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:31.560
So, throughout the play, Claudius is building
up an army to take on Norway and Denmark is

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:36.580
caught in a strange limbo between war and
not war. As often happens, the specter of

00:05:36.580 --> 00:05:41.230
external enemies leads the ruling powers to
search for enemies within, and we see a lot

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:45.990
of examples of Elsinore as a surveillance
society. Like, Hamlet’s not wrong when he

00:05:45.990 --> 00:05:49.700
tells Rosencrantz and Guildenstern “Denmark’s
a prison.”

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:53.310
The characters are closely watching each other;
I mean Gertrude and Claudius are watching

00:05:53.310 --> 00:05:57.990
Hamlet, so is Polonius, though he’s awfully
bad at it. Hamlet’s schoolmates, Rosencrantz

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:02.560
and Guildenstern are watching him closely
as Claudius is encouraging them to spy while

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:07.050
they throw back Danish grog and talk about
girls. Ophelia is watching Hamlet, too, but

00:06:07.050 --> 00:06:11.139
Hamlet isn’t watching her, because he’s
too busy staring at Claudius, trying to figure

00:06:11.139 --> 00:06:15.000
out if he really did murder his father and
of course Hamlet also spends a lot of time

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.620
watching himself and then reciting anguished
soliloquies about it.

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:22.620
Personally, in the end, I’m more struck
my Hamlet’s narcissism than by his indecisiveness.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:25.540
Anyway, all of this is probably less a criticism

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:29.340
of Denmark, which is a perfectly nice place
full of herring sandwiches and competitive

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:34.320
handball, than it is a commentary on Elizabethan
England, a place notorious for spying and

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:38.020
also the place where Shakespeare actually
lived. There were all sorts of anti-royal,

00:06:38.020 --> 00:06:43.980
anti-Catholic conspiracies going and Elizabeth
I ran a whole network of spies to help discover

00:06:43.980 --> 00:06:49.160
them — sort of like M in James Bond, but with
more tiaras. Even Christopher Marlowe, Shakespeare’s

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:52.940
rival and one of the most badass playwright’s
ever, was a spy. So the court of Elsinore

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:57.110
can be read as a commentary on Shakespeare’s
own environment, in which being tried and

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:00.479
beheaded for secret treason was kind of a
national pastime.

00:07:00.479 --> 00:07:04.250
Thanks, Thought Bubble. So Hamlet is a play
about watching and being watched. Something

00:07:04.250 --> 00:07:07.490
that we’re all pretty familiar with these
days, but it’s also a play about doubling

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:09.860
and mirroring.
This is a common Shakespearian thing but it

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:12.650
gets to some really core questions about being
a person.

00:07:12.650 --> 00:07:16.810
Like are people really capable of change,
can they become different people over time,

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:21.440
and when you look in the mirror are you seeing
the person that is actually you? Are you the

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:25.510
person you imagine yourself to be?
So, there are at least two Hamlets in this

00:07:25.510 --> 00:07:29.600
play, right, there is the old dead King Hamlet
who goes around haunting the Elsinore battlements

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:33.320
and our hero who is supposed to avenge that
old Hamlet .

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:37.380
But the living Hamlet is also split into two
people: the one who wants to kill Claudius

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.900
and the one who’s like, “You know maybe
not. Maybe I should just be a grad student.”

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:44.740
And some critics argue that the Hamlet who
returns home from the pirate adventure is

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:49.050
yet another person, because he is a very different
guy from the one who left.

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:53.680
And you can even see Ophelia as a kind of
extreme, subversive double for Hamlet, like

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:58.160
what Hamlet might be like if he were robbed
of all of his power and agency.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:01.540
And then obviously when the actors perform
their play The Murder of Gonzago, they’re

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:05.460
mirroring all the recent events in Elsinore.
But it’s not a regular mirror right. It’s

