00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:53.440
These mirrors also underscore the perpetual
cycle of violence at the heart of the revenge

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:56.529
tragedy which you’ll no doubt remember from
our talk of ancient Greek stories.

00:08:56.529 --> 00:08:59.450
Like in these tragedies the desire for vengeance

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:05.200
ultimately corrupts the revenger and he or
she has to die, too. Each murder has to be

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.540
answered for with another murder until we
are out of people who can die.

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:13.870
A good example of this unending violence is
old Hamlet’s ghost, who can’t rest in

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:18.529
this grave until he’s avenged. Now, the
critics Andrew Bennett and Nicholas Royle

00:09:18.529 --> 00:09:24.420
describe ghosts as “the very embodiment
of strange repetition or recurrence: it is

00:09:24.420 --> 00:09:29.450
a revenant, it comes back”
Okay, but it comes back from where? Like ghosts

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:35.089
don’t really fit into Hamlet’s understanding
of death. He describes death as “The undiscover’d

00:09:35.089 --> 00:09:40.790
country, from whose born / No traveller returns.”
Except his dad, apparently.

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:44.810
In fact, one way to read it is that the ghost’s
fate is in some ways aligned with Catholic

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:50.640
purgatory, “confin’d to fast in fires
/ till the foul crimes done in my days of

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:57.060
nature / are burnt and purg’d away.” And
Hamlet seems to fear something similar, “For

00:09:57.060 --> 00:10:01.920
in that sleep of death what dreams may come.”
Though it’s also worth nothing that Hamlet

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:07.080
wonders if the ghost really is his father.
Hamlet has to ask if the ghost is a “spirit

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:11.490
of health or goblin damn'd.”
Regardless, the ghost makes Hamlet wonder

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:15.970
about the consequences of his actions. I mean
here’s Hamlet saying, “Can this ghost

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:22.100
(whose name I remind you is Hamlet) be trusted?
Is justice the business of people or of God.

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:26.510
Now obviously there are no easy answers to
those questions but earthly justice is clearly

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:31.590
corrupt in this play — I mean Claudius has usurped
the kingdom and there’s evidence that old King

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:34.160
Hamlet might not have been the greatest ruler
either.

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:37.240
And Claudius is already being punished spiritually,
although it’s not clear whether it comes

00:10:37.240 --> 00:10:43.580
from himself or from god, but, like, at one point
he tries to pray and finds that he actually can’t:

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:49.820
“My words fly up, my thoughts remain below
words without thought never to heaven go,”

00:10:49.820 --> 00:10:52.140
Now prayer was seen as cleansing and in that

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:57.220
scene Hamlet decides not to kill Claudius
because he believes that Claudius is praying

00:10:57.220 --> 00:11:01.440
and therefore will be cleansed of his sin
and will go straight to heaven if Hamlet killed

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:04.330
him right then.
And that wouldn’t be fair! Of course, actually,

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:09.029
if he’d just killed Claudius in that moment
due to the thoughts not going up to heaven

00:11:09.029 --> 00:11:13.100
everything would’ve been fine. I mean not
for Claudius, but you know, for justice.

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:17.910
So should Hamlet act? Should he let diving
justice take its course? Does divine justice

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:22.380
only work through people? Even I can’t decide!
But Mr Green, Mr Green, in the end how does

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:25.870
Hamlet make up his mind though?
Well, Me From the Past, when he finally makes

00:11:25.870 --> 00:11:29.670
up his mind he’s dieing, right? He has like
seconds left to live.

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:34.380
Ultimately, Hamlet is a great play for its
aphorisms, and its language, and its ambiguity,

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:40.340
but also because it brilliantly captures the
fact that we do not know what we are doing.

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:43.860
Hamlet doesn’t struggle to decide a course
of action because he’s young or because

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:48.020
he’s an academic or because he’s a narcissist.
He struggles because he’s human.

